description:
## Goal

`ir_lower` consumes the now-spanned AST (.20.2) and produces IR. The IR's `Var`, `BlockId`, `FnId` are bare `u32` indices (`src/fz_ir.rs:67-73`). This ticket adds parallel side-tables on `Module` so that any IR position — a `Var`, a `(BlockId, stmt_idx)`, a `FnId` — can be mapped back to a source `Span` and (for Vars) to the original source name.

The side-table approach (rather than fattening `Prim`/`Stmt`/`Term`) was decided in the .20 epic. Keeping the IR types narrow matters for codegen readability and for the diff with the upstream-lowered form.

## Dependencies

- Requires .20.2 (AST spans).
- Independent of .20.3 — `ir_lower` doesn't run inside macros; it sees post-resolve, post-expand AST.

## Data structures

Extend `src/fz_ir.rs::Module` with:

```rust
pub struct Module {
    pub fns: Vec<FnIr>,
    pub schemas: Vec<Schema>,
    // existing fields...

    /// Source spans for IR positions. None of these are required to be
    /// populated (a builder that doesn't care can leave them empty); the
    /// renderer treats absence as "no span available".
    pub source: SourceInfo,
}

#[derive(Debug, Default, Clone)]
pub struct SourceInfo {
    /// Var -> defining-site span (the source position where the value was
    /// introduced: a literal, a pattern binding, the result of a call, etc.)
    pub var_span: Vec<Span>,        // indexed by Var.0; Span::DUMMY if unknown
    /// Var -> source name (empty string for compiler-introduced temps).
    pub var_name: Vec<String>,
    /// Span per (fn_id, block_id, stmt_idx) for Stmts (Let bindings).
    /// Stored as nested vecs aligned with `FnIr::blocks[].stmts`. For
    /// space, only fns/blocks that have any non-DUMMY entries are stored;
    /// absence => all DUMMY.
    pub stmt_spans: HashMap<(FnId, BlockId), Vec<Span>>,
    /// Span per (fn_id, block_id) for the block's terminator.
    pub term_span: HashMap<(FnId, BlockId), Span>,
    /// Span per fn for the source definition site (FnDef.span).
    pub fn_span: Vec<Span>,         // indexed by FnId.0; Span::DUMMY if synthesized
}
```

Storage discussion: the `HashMap<(FnId, BlockId), …>` shape costs ~32 bytes per entry; an alternative is `Vec<Vec<Span>>` indexed by `FnId.0` and `BlockId.0`. Pick **HashMap** for v1: blocks within a fn are referenced sparsely by id (BlockIds are not necessarily dense), and the HashMap is simpler to wire up while ir_lower / liveness juggles block creation. Switch to dense vecs later if profiling shows it.

## ir_lower changes

`LowerCtx` (`src/ir_lower.rs:104-121`) already carries `env: HashMap<String, Var>`. Add:

```rust
pub struct LowerCtx {
    // ... existing ...

    /// Built up alongside `env`: Var.0 -> source name. Compiler temps get
    /// `""`. Persisted to Module.source.var_name when lowering finishes.
    var_names: Vec<String>,
    /// Var.0 -> defining-site span.
    var_spans: Vec<Span>,
}
```

Hook points (every `next_temp` or `fb.fresh_var()` site in `ir_lower.rs`):

- When introducing a Var for a pattern variable (Pattern::Var, Pattern::As), set `var_names[v.0] = name.clone()` and `var_spans[v.0] = pattern.span`.
- When introducing a Var for the result of a Prim, set `var_names[v.0] = ""` and `var_spans[v.0] = expr.span` (the span of the source `Expr` that produced this Prim).
- When introducing block params (entry block from fn params, or continuation params), copy names/spans from the corresponding pattern or, for the result-slot of a Call's continuation, the call expression's span.

For `Stmt::Let` emission, push `expr.span` into `stmt_spans[(cur_fn, cur_block)]` aligned with the stmt index. For terminators, set `term_span[(cur_fn, cur_block)]` at the moment of finalization.

For `FnIr` creation: `fn_span[FnId.0]` = the originating `FnDef.span` (top-level fn) or the synthesizing call site (closures, continuations). Closures lifted from `Expr::Lambda` use the lambda's span. Continuations (CPS split, no source equivalent) use the *Call expression's* span — they exist to receive the call's result, so that's the user-visible position.

## What the codegen sees

ir_codegen doesn't need to look at `SourceInfo` — the type-checker (ir_typer) does. But: the codegen-emitted `Diagnostic::message` for things like "trampoline overflow" or "schema lookup failed" can attach a span by looking up the offending FnId/BlockId. This is for .20.7, not here. .20.4 just makes the data available.

## ir_typer can now stop saying "v3"

Once this lands, the existing `ir_typer.rs:598-603` message can become (after .20.5/.20.6/.20.8 land — but the data is here):

```rust
format!("`{}` here has no possible value", module.source.var_name[v.0])
// rendered at module.source.var_span[v.0]
```

That's what .20.8 wires up. .20.4 just exposes the data.

## Deliverables

- `SourceInfo` on `Module`.
- ir_lower populates it everywhere a Var is introduced or a Stmt/Term emitted.
- Builders in `src/fz_ir.rs::FnBuilder` / `ModuleBuilder` extended to accept spans (default = DUMMY for callers that don't care, but ir_lower MUST supply them — verified by a `#[cfg(test)] assert` in lowering or a debug-only check).
- Closures and continuations: span policy as described.
- Tests:
  - Lower `fixtures/modules.fz`. Verify `source.var_name` has `"x"` for the param of `double`, and `source.var_span` points at the `x` pattern token on line 2.
  - Verify a CPS-split continuation has `fn_span` pointing at its originating Call expression.

## Non-goals

- Consuming the spans (.20.7 / .20.8).
- Optimizing the storage layout (HashMap is fine for v1).
- Tracking IR-level transformations (frame inlining .11.15) — those happen after this; the new IR they emit just propagates spans verbatim.
